              <h3>What is American Sign Language?</h3>
              <br><br>
              <p>Sign languages differ across countries and even within regions. There is no universal sign
                language. In America, the Deaf community uses American Sign Language (ASL). ASL is a complete,
                grammatically complex language. The National Association of the Deaf explains that in ASL, “the
                shape, placement, and movement of the hands, as well as facial expressions and body movements,
                all play important parts in conveying information.”1
                 ASL is not a communication code designed to
                represent English</p>

                <p>Attaining proficiency in ASL mirrors that of other spoken languages. Proficiency requires extensive
                  instruction and immersion in the culture and language. In terms of ASL, this occurs with ongoing use
                  at home, in school, and/or with members of the Deaf community. </p>

                </div>
